<section xml:id="sec_capacitors-in-circuits" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Capacitors in Circuits: Series and Parallel</title>

	<p>You learned about capacitors in Section <xref ref="sec_capacitors"/>. Capacitors can also be elements within a circuit!</p>
			
	<video youtube="jlTt8b-2ZQc"><description>Setting up capacitors in series and parallel circuits.</description></video>
			
	<p>Combining capacitors in series and in parallel is opposite to how you combine resistors.</p>

	<figure xml:id="CD_C">
			<caption>The circuit diagram representation for a capacitor.</caption>
			<image source="CD_C.png" width = "10%" ><description>Two parallel lines of equal length representing a capacitor.</description></image>
		</figure>

	<exercises>
		<title>Activities</title>
		<exercise>
			<p>Which of the following statements about capacitors do you think is true? (You may select more than one answer.)</p>
			<ol type="a">
				<li><p>Capacitors in series have the same voltage.</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in series have the same charge.</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in parallel have the same voltage.</p></li>
				<li><p>Capacitors in parallel have the same charge.</p></li>
			</ol>
			<p>Explain your reasoning.</p>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
	
	<p>In class, you will derive the rules below for adding capacitors.</p>
	
		<definition>
		<title>Adding Capacitors in Series</title>
		<statement>
			<p>If <m>N</m> capacitors are in series, the equivalent capacitance is: <me>\frac{1}{C_{\mathrm{total}}} = \sum_{i = 1}^{N} \frac{1}{C_i} = \frac{1}{C_1} + \frac{1}{C_2} + \frac{1}{C_3} + \dots</me></p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<definition>
		<title>Adding Capacitors in Parallel</title>
		<statement>
			<p>If <m>N</m> capacitors are in parallel, the equivalent capacitance is: <me>C_{\mathrm{total}} = \sum_{i = 1}^{N} C_i = C_1 + C_2 + C_3 + \dots</me></p>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	
